> Has there been thought to including something like circular-dependency-plugin by default? I think it could help head off these kinds of issues by catching circular dependencies early and strongly recommending against them / encouraging a pattern of whitelisting exceptions for the few cases they're needed. I like that Rollup warns on this circular dependency case. But maybe that's too opinionated to include in the core?

I had some ideas to detect circular dependencies and improve optimization based on them. But that got a bit stuck as there are dirty ways to hide them so detection would not be relieable enough:

```
// index.js
require("./a");

export function innocentFunction() {
  // lazy imported
  require("./a");
}

// a.js
const b = require("./b");

// b.js
const { innocentFunction } = require("./index.js");
innocentFunction();
```

The module graph is non-circular, but execution is circular at runtime.

So this gets pretty tricky. Probably only possible for ESM. Still tricky when interacting with CJS or other dynamic things.

> In this case there's also a runtime error in production mode (`Uncaught ReferenceError: Cannot access 't' before initialization` under 5.0.0-beta.16, using default `--mode production` behavior with no config file). But agreed that this case seems very rare and rewriting to avoid it is a workable solution.

That's actually a bug.

There seem to be wrong behavior for function declarations without name. This works-around the problem:

``` diff
-export default function () {
+export default function name() {
   console.log('shared import');
 }
```

function declarations without name in export default is a little bit of an edge case.

@sokra I just ran into another manifestation of this issue in an unreleased version of `openai` I'm working on for Stainless API.  I made [this repo](https://github.com/jedwards1211/webpack-circular-import-bug) to demonstrate the issue.  In this case, the variable is defined by the time it's referenced when running with ES module semantics, but the webpack dev bundle throws a `TypeError`.

Hopefully we'll simplify our import graph, but I have a pretty clear idea how to solve this in Webpack, it would be a somewhat significant change, but hopefully you think my proposal here would be a good solution.

The crux of the problem is that
```ts
export { Chat } from "./chat.js";
export { ChatCompletion, Completions } from "./completions.js";
```
gets webpacked into
```js
__webpack_require__.r(__webpack_exports__);
/* harmony export */ __webpack_require__.d(__webpack_exports__, {
/* harmony export */   Chat: () => (/* reexport safe */ _chat_js__WEBPACK_IMPORTED_MODULE_0__.Chat),
/* harmony export */   Completions: () => (/* reexport safe */ _completions_js__WEBPACK_IMPORTED_MODULE_1__.Completions)
/* harmony export */ });
/* harmony import */ var _chat_js__WEBPACK_IMPORTED_MODULE_0__ = __webpack_require__(/*! ./chat.js */ "./src/chat.ts");
/* harmony import */ var _completions_js__WEBPACK_IMPORTED_MODULE_1__ = __webpack_require__(/*! ./completions.js */ "./src/completions.ts");
```
Where, unlike when ES Modules are initializing, `_completions_js__WEBPACK_IMPORTED_MODULE_1__` doesn't even reference the module in question until after `"./chat.js"` initializes.  But code in `chat.js` circularly tries to read from it, causing a `TypeError`.

The solution would be to create empty module objects and get references to them before evaluating imported modules, via a new `__webpack_require__.initModule` or some such function:
```js
__webpack_require__.r(__webpack_exports__);
/* harmony export */ __webpack_require__.d(__webpack_exports__, {
/* harmony export */   Chat: () => (/* reexport safe */ _chat_js__WEBPACK_IMPORTED_MODULE_0__.Chat),
/* harmony export */   Completions: () => (/* reexport safe */ _completions_js__WEBPACK_IMPORTED_MODULE_1__.Completions)
/* harmony export */ });

// Get references to the empty modules before evaluating imports.
// `_completions_js__WEBPACK_IMPORTED_MODULE_1__` will be empty at first,
// but it will get populated when `chat.js` imports `completions.js`.

/* harmony import */ var _chat_js__WEBPACK_IMPORTED_MODULE_0__ = __webpack_require__.initModule(/*! ./chat.js */ "./src/chat.ts");
/* harmony import */ var _completions_js__WEBPACK_IMPORTED_MODULE_1__ = __webpack_require__.initModule(/*! ./completions.js */ "./src/completions.ts");

// Actually evaluate the imports
/* harmony import */ __webpack_require__(/*! ./chat.js */ "./src/chat.ts");
/* harmony import */ __webpack_require__(/*! ./completions.js */ "./src/completions.ts");
```

What do you think?  If you're open to this I'd love to work on a PR.
